Synecdoche, New York

2008 Directed by Charlie Kaufman

Synopsis

A theater director struggles with his work, and the women in his life, as he attempts to create a life-size replica of New York inside a warehouse as part of his new play.

  • Review by karsten ★★★★★ 50

    Watched this morning and have since been going back, rewatching scenes, figuring out how to write this review, and reading up on some other people's takes. This film is much bigger and more personal than...anything I've seen in my life. To summarize everything I have to say about this and everything it meant to me in one review would be absolutely silly. Will probably be making a video on it soon, but even that won't do it justice. Something (many things) about this film is too powerful, too personal, and too honest for me to put into words. Sometimes you just know when you've seen the best movie you've ever seen, that's what happened with Synecdoche, New York. Why am I so sad?

  • Review by neuroprismatic cinephile🏳️‍🌈 ★★★★★ 1

    Synecdoche, New York. 2008. Directed by Charlie Kaufman.

    Charlie Kaufman’s profound screenplay on the inevitability of death (as long as we are in this human body, we will experience suffering) as life extension, vitamins, and health is promoted all around us. However, the Pandemic has put a different spotlight on death and dying for me as it was amplified all around us. However, Charlie Kaufman’s Synedoche, New York is like a perpetual rendering of his thoughts on relationships, life, death, and dying all while it is metamorphosing into brilliant schizophrenic cubist plays that communicate with each other. Philip Seymour Hoffman is in his element and should have been given all of the award circuit accolades for this performance. Michelle Williams,… more
